      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Evergreen content</strong> is content that remains relevant, accurate, and useful months or years after publication, unlike news articles or trend pieces that expire quickly. "How to unclog a drain" stays useful in 2029. "Top TikTok trends for March 2026" doesn't. <strong>60% of pages ranking in Google's top 10 are 3+ years old</strong> — evergreen content accumulates authority over time like compound interest.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Top-10 pages that are 3+ yrs old</div>
            <div class="tms-value">60%</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Content</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Recommended mix</div>
            <div class="tms-value">70% evergreen</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Most content strategies spend budget chasing trend-driven traffic spikes. Evergreen strategy builds a content library that generates traffic indefinitely. The production cost is fixed. The organic traffic compounds. Over 24 months, a single well-executed evergreen article can generate more total visits than 50 trend-driven posts combined.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is evergreen content?</h2>
        <p>Evergreen content answers questions that people consistently ask — questions where the answer doesn't change month to month. The term borrows from forestry: evergreen trees retain their leaves year-round, unlike deciduous trees that shed them seasonally. Evergreen content retains its relevance year-round.</p>
        <p>Examples of evergreen topics by category:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>How-to guides</strong> — "How to fix a running toilet," "How to write a meta description," "How to calculate cost per lead"</li>
          <li><strong>Definitions and glossaries</strong> — "What is a canonical URL," "What is CAC," "What is a 301 redirect"</li>
          <li><strong>Comparisons</strong> — "301 vs 302 redirect," "SEO vs PPC," "on-page vs off-page SEO"</li>
          <li><strong>Best practices</strong> — "SEO best practices," "email marketing best practices," "how to write a title tag"</li>
          <li><strong>Checklists and templates</strong> — "Content audit checklist," "SEO checklist for new pages," "editorial calendar template"</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Non-evergreen examples (avoid as the core of your strategy): "Top Instagram trends for Q2 2026," "Recap of the 2025 HubSpot INBOUND conference," "Google's March 2026 core update: what changed."</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why old pages dominate Google's top results</div>
          <p>Google's ranking algorithm rewards pages that have <strong>accumulated backlinks, engagement signals, and editorial updates over time</strong>. A 3-year-old evergreen article that gets refreshed annually outperforms a new article on the same topic in most competitive niches. Age is not a ranking factor directly, but the signals that come with age — backlinks, user trust, click-through rate — are.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why evergreen content matters for organic growth</h2>
        <p>Evergreen content produces a fundamentally different ROI curve than trend-driven content:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Compounding traffic.</strong> A single evergreen post published today may generate 50 visits in month one, 200 in month six, and 800+ monthly by year two as rankings improve and backlinks accumulate. Traffic compounds; production cost stays fixed.</li>
          <li><strong>Lower cost per visit over time.</strong> The marginal cost of each additional visitor from an evergreen article approaches zero after publication. Each trend-driven article resets the cost counter.</li>
          <li><strong>Foundation for topical authority.</strong> A cluster of evergreen articles on a topic tells Google your site is the authoritative resource. Individual trend posts don't build this signal.</li>
          <li><strong>Supports timely content.</strong> When you publish a timely piece, linking back to related evergreen content passes authority and context. The timely content has a short shelf life; the evergreen content captures the long-term traffic from searchers discovering the topic for the first time.</li>
          <li><strong>Backlink magnet.</strong> Other websites link to definitions, guides, and how-tos for years after publication. Trend posts collect backlinks for days, then stop. A glossary term like this one will earn backlinks for as long as the topic is relevant.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How to create evergreen content that ranks</h2>
        <p>Three disciplines separate evergreen content that compounds from evergreen content that flatlines:</p>
        <p><strong>Choose topics with stable search demand.</strong> Use Google Trends to verify consistent year-round search volume before committing to a topic. A query showing flat or slowly growing demand over 3+ years is a reliable evergreen candidate. Avoid topics showing strong seasonality spikes unless you're specifically targeting seasonal windows.</p>
        <p><strong>Match format to search intent.</strong> Google shows which format wins for each query — check the current top-10 results. If they're all step-by-step guides, write a step-by-step guide. If they're comparison tables, build a comparison table. Format-intent mismatch is why technically well-written evergreen content fails to rank.</p>
        <p><strong>Update periodically.</strong> Review top-performing evergreen pages every 6-12 months. Refresh statistics, update examples, add new sections, remove outdated information. A page last updated in 2021 signals staleness to Google's freshness signals even when the topic is inherently timeless. The refresh date in your schema markup matters.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Evergreen content types — performance by category</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
