        <h2 id="examples">Real evergreen content examples that generated measurable ROI</h2>
        <p>These cases show what evergreen content produces at 12-24 months after publication.</p>

        <h3>1. Plumbing company how-to guide</h3>
        <p>A plumbing company published "How to Fix a Running Toilet: Step-by-Step Guide." It ranked in the top 3 within 4 months and generated 800+ visits monthly by year two. Production cost: one afternoon with a plumber and a writer. Value generated: hundreds of leads over 24 months, with zero additional production cost after publication.</p>

        <h3>2. SaaS company 200-term marketing glossary</h3>
        <p>A SaaS company built a 200-term marketing glossary targeting "what is [term]" queries. Each term page is a standalone evergreen article optimized for a single definition query. Combined, the glossary drives 15,000+ organic visits monthly — all from content that, once written, requires only periodic updates to maintain rankings.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Evergreen content vs. timely content — the strategic balance</h2>
        <p>Neither type alone is sufficient. The recommended split is 70% evergreen, 30% timely.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Evergreen content strengths</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Compounds in traffic over 12-36 months</li>
              <li>Earns backlinks for years after publication</li>
              <li>Builds topical authority for an entire subject area</li>
              <li>Can be repurposed across formats indefinitely</li>
              <li>Cost per visit approaches zero over time</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Timely content strengths</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Generates immediate traffic spikes from news queries</li>
              <li>Earns links from journalists and newsletters</li>
              <li>Demonstrates brand currency and awareness</li>
              <li>Fuels social sharing in the first 48 hours</li>
              <li>Tests new topic areas before committing evergreen resources</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for evergreen content</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Target stable search queries, not trend-dependent ones.</strong> Verify 3+ years of flat demand in Google Trends before investing in a long-form evergreen piece.</li>
          <li><strong>Write the most comprehensive resource on the topic.</strong> Evergreen content earns rankings by being the definitive answer — not just a good answer. Match or exceed the depth of current top-ranking results.</li>
          <li><strong>Build topical clusters around your evergreen pillars.</strong> Each evergreen pillar (e.g., "SEO for small businesses") should link to 5-10 supporting articles. The cluster tells Google you own the topic.</li>
          <li><strong>Add a "last updated" date in your page schema and visible UI.</strong> Freshness signals matter. A page that shows "Updated June 2026" outperforms an identical page showing "Published 2022" with no refresh indicator.</li>
          <li><strong>Include data, statistics, and real examples.</strong> Evergreen content earns backlinks when others cite your specific numbers. "Studies show content marketing is effective" earns no links. "60% of Google top-10 results are 3+ years old (Ahrefs)" earns hundreds.</li>
          <li><strong>Repurpose systematically.</strong> Every evergreen article should generate at least 3 social posts, one LinkedIn carousel, and one YouTube or podcast segment. The topic is stable — the investment in research pays across every format.</li>
          <li><strong>Schedule annual reviews.</strong> Create a calendar reminder for each major evergreen piece. At the anniversary, review statistics, check competing pages, add any new sections, and update the schema date. Pages that get refreshed annually maintain rankings; pages that don't eventually fall.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — building all-evergreen with no timely content</div>
          <p>A 100% evergreen strategy misses short-term traffic spikes from news events and trends in your industry. It also looks stale to repeat visitors who see the same content every visit. The 70/30 split works because timely content keeps current visitors engaged while evergreen content builds the long-term traffic foundation.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common evergreen content mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Calling trend-dependent content evergreen</strong> — "The best SEO tools in 2026" is not evergreen. "How to evaluate an SEO tool" is. The former expires; the latter doesn't.</li>
          <li><strong>No annual refresh process</strong> — even timeless topics accumulate stale statistics and outdated examples. Without a scheduled refresh, evergreen content gradually underperforms newer competitors who keep their content current.</li>
          <li><strong>Thin evergreen content</strong> — 500-word definitions rank for zero-competition queries but can't compete for high-value terms. Depth is the competitive advantage of evergreen content.</li>
          <li><strong>No internal linking to or from evergreen content</strong> — evergreen articles that sit in isolation without internal links from newer content or to related evergreen pieces accumulate authority slowly. Link every new post to relevant evergreen articles.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating evergreen content as "publish and forget"</strong> — publication is day one; the compounding happens over 24-36 months of refreshes, link building, and internal linking. Teams that publish and move on leave most of the value unrealized.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What's the opposite of evergreen content?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Timely or topical content — news coverage, trend reports, seasonal posts, and event recaps. These have high short-term impact but lose relevance quickly. Both types serve a content strategy: evergreen builds compounding organic traffic, timely content captures momentary spikes.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How do you know if a topic is truly evergreen?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Check Google Trends for the search volume over 2+ years. Stable or growing demand with no seasonal spikes confirms evergreen status. Also ask: will this information remain accurate in 12 months? If yes, it qualifies.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How often should you update evergreen content?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Review evergreen content annually at minimum. Update statistics, add recent examples, verify accuracy, and expand sections that have received high engagement. Pages that receive regular refreshes maintain and improve search rankings over time.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is the ideal content calendar ratio of evergreen to timely?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>70% evergreen, 30% timely is the recommended content calendar split for most content-focused businesses. The evergreen 70% builds compounding organic traffic; the timely 30% captures trend-driven spikes and gives the team reasons to engage existing audiences.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can evergreen content be repurposed?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes — and it should be. A single evergreen blog post can become a LinkedIn carousel, a YouTube explainer, a podcast episode, a downloadable guide, and multiple social posts. The stable topic means the underlying research and examples remain valid across every format.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

